    "eyebrow": "Primary Sources Workshop",
    "num": "01",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">01</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Primary Sources Workshop</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Key Archival Collections on Texican History</h2><ul><li>Explore major archival collections: Texas State Library, Yale, Berkeley, and local Texas archives</li><li>Types of documents: letters, treaties, government records, and personal accounts</li><li>Importance of original documents for authentic historical understanding</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Primary sources such as letters and treaties provide direct evidence of Texican life and political context. Engaging with these archives helps learners develop critical skills in historical interpretation and source evaluation. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s12\">[12]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s15\">[15]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Examine a letter from a Texican settler describing frontier challenges to understand daily life and political tensions.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Review a selected treaty excerpt and identify the parties involved and the treaty’s implications for Texican relations.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming all primary sources are unbiased or complete; many reflect specific perspectives or agendas.</p></div></div>",
