    "num": "05",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">05</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Terminology Evolution</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">From Texican to Texian to Texan: An Overview</h2><ul><li>Texican: Mexican Texas residents (1820–1836)</li><li>Texian: Residents during the Republic of Texas era (1836–1845)</li><li>Texan: Post-annexation U.S. state residents (post-1845)</li><li>Terminology reflects political and cultural shifts</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">The terms Texican, Texian, and Texan mark distinct historical periods and identities, illustrating evolving political allegiances and cultural self-perceptions. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A settler identified as Texican in 1830 would be called Texian after 1836 following Texas independence.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Create a timeline placing these terms alongside key historical events.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Using the terms interchangeably without regard to their historical context.</p></div></div>",
