    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">06</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Terminology Deep Dive</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Origins and Usage of 'Texican' in Mexican Texas</h2><ul><li>'Texican' derived from Spanish 'Tejicano', denoting Mexican citizens in Texas</li><li>Used primarily during Mexican governance (1820–1836)</li><li>Signified legal status and cultural affiliation with Mexico</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">The term 'Texican' reflects the Mexican period of Texas history and the residents’ citizenship and cultural ties before independence. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Mexican census records list residents as 'Texicanos', indicating official recognition of this identity.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Analyze a primary source using 'Texican' and discuss its implications for identity.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming 'Texican' was a general term for all Texas residents regardless of period.</p></div></div>",
    "paper": {
      "secnum": "Deep Dive 06",
      "h": "Linguistic and Political Context of 'Texican'",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> The term 'Texican' reflects the Mexican period of Texas history and the residents’ citizenship and cultural ties before independence.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from lauriemooremoore.com; everything-everywhere.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>'Texican' derived from Spanish 'Tejicano', denoting Mexican citizens in Texas</li><li>Used primarily during Mexican governance (1820–1836)</li><li>Signified legal status and cultural affiliation with Mexico</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Mexican census records list residents as 'Texicanos', indicating official recognition of this identity.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Analyze a primary source using 'Texican' and discuss its implications for identity.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming 'Texican' was a general term for all Texas residents regardless of period.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> lauriemooremoore.com; everything-everywhere.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup></p>"
    }
