    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">08</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Terminology in Primary Sources</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Examining Usage of Texican, Texian, and Texan in Documents</h2><ul><li>Analyze official documents, letters, and newspapers for terminology</li><li>Note context and audience influencing term choice</li><li>Identify shifts in self-identification and external labeling</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Primary sources reveal how terminology was used in practice, reflecting identity politics and social dynamics. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A newspaper editorial from 1840 uses 'Texian' to promote Republic nationalism.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Compare two documents from different periods and discuss terminology differences.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Ignoring the influence of document type or audience on terminology choice.</p></div></div>",
