      "h": "Selective Assimilation in Texican Culture",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Texican culture transformed through selective assimilation, balancing new Anglo influences with enduring Mexican and Spanish heritage amid political change.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from jinxschwartz.com; lauriemooremoore.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Assimilation involved adopting Anglo-American customs and laws</li><li>Retention of Mexican and Spanish traditions persisted</li><li>Political shifts accelerated identity renegotiation</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Texicans adopted Anglo-style land ownership laws while maintaining Catholic religious practices.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Discuss how Texicans balanced assimilation with cultural preservation.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Viewing assimilation as complete cultural replacement rather than selective adaptation.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> jinxschwartz.com; lauriemooremoore.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup></p>"
