    "eyebrow": "Critical Evaluation",
    "num": "25",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">25</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Critical Evaluation</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Identifying Bias in Secondary Sources</h2><ul><li>Recognize author perspective and purpose</li><li>Detect language that signals bias or opinion</li><li>Compare multiple secondary accounts for discrepancies</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Secondary sources often reflect the author's viewpoint or agenda, which can introduce bias. Critical evaluation requires identifying these biases to understand the reliability and perspective of the narrative (s2, s3, s4). <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s3\">[3]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s4\">[4]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Compare two secondary sources describing Texican interactions with Mexican authorities; note differences in tone and emphasis.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Review a secondary source excerpt and highlight phrases that suggest bias or subjective interpretation.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming all secondary sources are equally objective without questioning author background or context.</p></div></div>",
    "paper": {
      "secnum": "Deep Dive 25",
      "h": "Understanding Bias in Historical Narratives",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Secondary sources often reflect the author's viewpoint or agenda, which can introduce bias. Critical evaluation requires identifying these biases to understand the reliability and perspective of the narrative (s2, s3, s4).</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from jinxschwartz.com; facebook.com; en.wikipedia.org. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Recognize author perspective and purpose</li><li>Detect language that signals bias or opinion</li><li>Compare multiple secondary accounts for discrepancies</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Compare two secondary sources describing Texican interactions with Mexican authorities; note differences in tone and emphasis.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Review a secondary source excerpt and highlight phrases that suggest bias or subjective interpretation.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming all secondary sources are equally objective without questioning author background or context.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> jinxschwartz.com; facebook.com; en.wikipedia.org <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s3\">[3]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s4\">[4]</sup></p>"
    }
