    "eyebrow": "Critical Evaluation",
    "num": "26",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">26</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Critical Evaluation</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Corroborating Secondary Sources with Primary Evidence</h2><ul><li>Use primary documents to verify secondary claims</li><li>Identify gaps or contradictions between sources</li><li>Assess the reliability of primary sources themselves</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Primary sources provide direct evidence from the time period, essential for validating or challenging secondary narratives. However, primary sources also require scrutiny for context and bias (s10, s11). <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s3\">[3]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Cross-check a secondary claim about Texican land grants with original land grant records from archival collections.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Select a secondary claim and find a corresponding primary source to confirm or question it.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Treating primary sources as infallible without considering their origin, purpose, or perspective.</p></div></div>",
